
The classes Scheduler and MIPScheduler provide a basic mechanism for 
scheduling threads/tasks with several priority queues.  The main difference
between Scheduler and MIPScheduler is that MIPScheduler provides an enumerated
type that defines the three priority queues that are used, while Scheduler 
allows the user to provide integers to index the priority queues.

The Scheduler and MIPScheduler objects maintain several queues and lists:
  algBlockedList	threads that are in the ThreadBlocked state, which are
				waiting for some algorithmic state to be true
  deadList		threads that are removed from the scheduler (these are
				not deleted for now).
  interrupts		threads that are in the ThreadWaiting state, which are
				waiting for some message to arrive
  threadGroup[i]	threads that are in the ThreadReady state, which are 
				waiting to run

int add(ThreadQueue* queue);

	The add method defines the next priority queue.  This method should be 
	called before all calls to the insert method.  The integer
	returned by add is the group number for that queue.  There are presently
	only three types of thread queues, so the following calls to add are 
	possible:

	sched.add(new ThreadQueue(round_robin));
		Implements a standard round-robin queue.
	sched.add(new ThreadQueue(time_weighted_priority));
		Implements a weighted queue that uses the amount of time used by
		a thread to update the thread priorities.
	sched.add(new ThreadQueue(bias_weighted_priority));
		Implements a weighted queue that simply uses the thread's bias 
		value (instead of the actual time taken) to update the thread 
		priorities.

void insert(ThreadObj* thread, int group=-1)
void insert(ThreadObj* thread, int group, int debug, char* name=NULL)

	The insert method inserts threads into one of the scheduler's queues.
	If the value of group is -1, then the scheduler uses the queue index
	specified by the thread's Group variable.  Otherwise, the insert
	method overwrites the threads Group variable.  If the debug variable
	is specified, then the thread's debug variable is overwritten.  When
	the name variable is given, debugging output from the scheduler will
	utilize this name tag.

int execute();

	The execute method runs the threads in the priority queues.  The 
	thread with the highest priority in the highest queue (lowest queue
	index) is run.  In each iteration of the scheduler, the following is
	done:
	  o Check the state of threads in the blocked list.  If a thread 
		becomes unblocked, move it to the interrupts or threadGroup 
		lists if it becomes unblocked.
	  o Check the state of threads in the interrupts list.  If a threads'
		message arrives, call its unwaiting method and move it
		to the blocked or threadGroup lists if a message arrives.
		(messages are checked in an arbitrary order that could, in
		principle affect the dynamics of the scheduler).
	  o Find the thread with the highest priority in the highest priority
		queue and run it.  
	  o If the thread returned OK, then move it into the appropriate list 
		or queue.  Otherwise move it to the deadlist.

static int termination_flag;

	This flag can be used by other threads to terminate the scheduler.
	(For example, see the methods in TermThread.H.)
	
	
